      <div>
        <h2 id="analytics" class="t-h3">Analytics (Plausible)</h2>
        <p>If you accept the Analytics category, this site loads a script from Plausible (<code>plausible.io</code>) to show us anonymised counts of visits and popular pages. Plausible does not use cookies or any other persistent identifier, does not collect personal data, and does not track you across other websites — it is not listed in the table above because it sets no cookie or storage of any kind. Nothing from Plausible loads until you accept this category.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="embeds" class="t-h3">External media embeds</h2>
        <p>Wherever this site can show an embedded YouTube video, it stays paused behind a placeholder — "External content is paused" — until either you accept the External media category once for the whole site, or press "Load this content" to load just that one video. We already request YouTube's privacy-enhanced <code>youtube-nocookie.com</code> domain once you do, though YouTube's own documentation notes this does not remove the need for consent or disclosure, which is why the placeholder and this category still apply.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="fonts" class="t-h3">Google Fonts</h2>
        <p>This site's two typefaces are loaded from Google's font-serving infrastructure (<code>fonts.googleapis.com</code> / <code>fonts.gstatic.com</code>) on every page view. Google's documentation states this service does not set cookies, so it is not listed in the table above — but the request itself does expose your IP address to Google, before any cookie banner can appear, because the page needs the fonts to render. We are considering self-hosting these fonts to remove this third-party request entirely; until then, we wanted this disclosed plainly rather than left out.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="outbound" class="t-h3">Links to other sites</h2>
        <p>Some links — for example, book links to Amazon, or resource-purchase links on Rethinking Society episode pages — simply take you to another website if you click them. Nothing is loaded from those sites until you do, and no cookie from them is ever set on this site. Once you follow such a link, you're on that provider's own site, governed by their own cookie and privacy policies, not this one.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="browser-controls" class="t-h3">Controlling cookies in your browser</h2>
        <p>Alongside the choices above, your browser lets you block or delete cookies and site data at any time from its own settings. Doing so may also remove the "remembered" choice this site's own consent banner relies on, meaning it may ask again on your next visit. If a third party (like YouTube) has already set its own cookies before you revoked consent here, deleting those fully may also require clearing them at the browser level, since we cannot reach into another provider's cookies from this website.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="changes" class="t-h3">Changes to this policy</h2>
        <p>If we add a new cookie, storage key, or third-party service, we will add it to the table above and — where it introduces a new category or materially changes what's collected — the consent version will be updated, which re-shows the banner so you can make a fresh choice.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 id="contact" class="t-h3">Contact</h2>
